fields: Most fractured bone of the face?
The zygomatic arch is continuous with {{c1::parts of the temporal bone}}
The vomer "plough" is continuous with the {{c1::maxillary palate}}
Where in the brain is CSF located?
The subclavian aretery supplies blood {{c1::posteriorly}} to the brain
The middle meningeal artery enters cranium through {{c1::foramen spinosum}}

The subararachnoid space is a {{c3::real space between the arachnoid and pia mater containing CSF}}
The subdural space is a {{c2::potential space between the dura mater and archnoid mater. Can have subdural hemorrhage}}
The epidural space is a p{{c1::otential space; can have bleeding/hemorrhage from the middle meningeal artery w/blood pooling between skull and brain}}
The scalp is {{c1::various soft tissue overlying the cranial regions}}
Buccinator: {{c1::prevents biting cheek when chewing and tightens cheek}}
The facial nerve emerges from the {{c1::stylomastoid}} foramen

A 17 y/o male presents to the ED due to injuries sustained during a motorcycle accident in which he was not wearing a helmet. The patient has a large, bleeding cut on his scalp just above the superciliary arches. Blood from the wound can easily pass into surrounding areas of the face and scalp by traveling through which layer of the scalp? Layer:
 
A.1
B.2
C.3
D.4
E.5

A 55 y/o male presents to his physician with complaints of acute, recurrent attacks of severe facial pain. He reports that the pain is most often triggered during shaving in the morning. The pain occurs mostly along his lower lip and chin. Which nerve is most likely involved in causing this patient’s symptoms?
 
A.Great auricular n.
B.Transverse cervical n.
C.V1
D.V2
E. V3

A 47 y/o male presents with a parotid gland calculus (stone). The stone obstructed the parotid duct near the papilla, and the patient complains of pain and swelling at the:
 
 
A. floor of the oral cavity near the posterior third of the tongue.
B. floor of the oral cavity on the sublingual caruncle.
C. lower oral vestibule opposite the incisor teeth.
D. mucosa overlying the hard palate.
 E. upper oral vestibule opposite the second molar.

What are the muscles of mastication?

Used to move the mandible for chewing & speech
Attach from somewhere on the cranium to the mandible
allows hinge and gliding movement as well as rotation

In the TMJ,

Pathway of pterygoid venous plexus? What does it communicate with?

-Drains through maxillary v.-→retromandibular v.-→ int. or ext. jugular v.
-Communicates with cavernous sinus
What is the autonomic innervation of the submandibular and sublingual glands?
How would a pt with left oculomotor nerve palsy present?

At resting position: left eye rotated down and out, eyelid drooping
Attempting to look right: eye is center, eyelid drooping
looking left: can look left, eyelid dropping
Symptoms of trochlear (superior oblique) left palsy?

-Head tilted to opposite side to compensate for diplopia
-can't look down and out or intort eye

Rods: sensitive to light
Cones: need lots of light to function
where you ideally want image focused
visual acuity, central vision, color vision, contains high concentration of cones. Contains macula lutea
If a sound is too loud, muscles can restrict movements of the {{c1::ossicles}} to dampen sound.

Innervation of middle ear?
Tensor tympani: {{c1::trigeminal n (CN V3)}}
Stapedius: {{c2::Facial n (CN VII)}}

In the cochlea, bony labyrinth contains {{c1::perilymph}}
Membranous labyrinth contains endolymph and sensory organs{{c2::}}
2 main components of vestibular system and their roles?

-Semicircular canals: detect rotational acceleration when head is in motion 
-Otolith organs: utricle/saccule; detects lear acceleration and detects head position in static equilibrium
How do otolith organs detect linear acceleration?

•Gelatin layer containing otoliths shifts due to gravity or linear movement.
•Hair cells detect shift, signal movement
-Saccule: vertical motion
-Utricle: horizontal motion

Aspirin
Antiplatelet
Treat: 81 mg to prevent thrombosis. 4-6 g for anti-inflammation
MOA: Covalently {{c1::acetylates}} and {{c1::irreversibly}} inhibits {{c1::cyclooxygenase-1 (cox -1)}} in platelet. Non reversable bind to TXA2 on platelets.
ADR: {{c1::GI Bleeding }} 2x over placebo
Distinguishing Characteristics: D/C for 10 days prior to surgery. Zero order elimination if >6g

Antiplatelet
Clopidogrel (likely on test)
Treat: 
MOA: Irreversibly block the ADP {{c1::P2Y12}} receptor (adenine diphosphate receptor) on platelets.
ADR: NO TAKE WITH {{c1::OMEPRAZOL}}. proton pump inhibitor omeprazole inhibits p450 2C19 which {{c1::degrades}} clopidogrel. Can also cause {{c1::Bleeding}}
Distinguishing Characteristics: it is a {{c1::Prodrug}}, need p450 2C19 to be active. Poor metabolizer of p450 2C19 polymorphism If Pt is a poor metabolizer, you will need to give them a {{c1::higher}} dose or they get  thrombosis. If ultra rapid metabolizer, give {{c1::lower}} dose or bleeding.

Antiplatelet

ABCiximab
Treat: unstable angina, IV infusion ( T1/2 2.5h)
MOA: binds to GP{{c1::IIb/IIIA}} receptor, blocking/inhibiting it. The final common pathway of platelet aggregation. Considered {{c1::most effective}} antiplatelet drugs
ADR: {{c1::Bleeding}}
Distinguishing Characteristics: hamanized antibody

MEMONIC: Americans Born Chinese block 2/3 kids GP IIB/ IIA

Anticoagulants
Unfractionated heparin  (likely on test)
Treat: IV or SubQ for major bleeds, unstable angina, DIC ( t1/2 = 2 hr)
MOA: Anti-thrombin III enzyme needs {{c1::heparin cofactor}} to bind to it and supercharge it (x1000) to degrade all active clotting factors with an "a" at the end (IIa, VIIa, Xa, Ixa, XIa, XIIa).
ADR: Bleeding, Heparin Induced {{c1::Thrombocytopenia}} (HIT) 1-5% incidence, see: micro-thrombosis. Platelet drops >{{c1::30}}%. {{c1::5-10}} days after beginning the heparin.
CI: hypersensitivity to heparin (HIT) (5%)
Distinguishing Characteristics: Heparin is {{c1::safe for pregnancy}} since large 20kda. Protamine is the antidote.

Low molecular weight Heparin does not destroy iia only Xa.
--Monitored by {{c1::aPTT}} (activated partial thromboplastin time) as 1.5–2.5 times baseline.
Heparin is highly acidic and negative (can be neutralized by antidote  which is basic and positive that is {{c1::protamine}})

Anticlotting notes:
VIIIa common for extrinsic and intrinsic
12 11 9 then go to 10 intrinsic
7 go to 10 extrinsic

Anticoagulants

Enoxaparin
Treat: (T1/2 4.5h)
MOA: enhance antithrombin {{c1::III}} to destroy clot factor {{c1::Xa}}, but not IIa (thrombin)
ADR: Do not use if history of {{c1::HIT}} hypersensativity.
Distinguishing Characteristics: Drug is ~ 5Kda, Less HIT (0.8% by LMWH vs 1-5% by heparin). Do not need to monitor {{c1::aPTT,}}
Protamine sulfate is only partially effective in reversing LMWH
CI: hypersensitivity to heparin (HIT) (0.8%)
Do not need to monitor anti Xa activity because anti Xa activity is very stable

Warfarin (likely on test)
Anticoagulants
Treat: orally to maintain anticoagulation therapy over long term (T1/2 {{c1::2-5}} days)
MOA: inhibit {{c1::vitamin k epoxide reductase}} (VKORC1), blocks cofactor synthases, decreases {{c1::pro-inactivated}} clot factors: {{c1::II}}, VII, IX, {{c1::X}}
ADR: Bleeding, NOT FOR {{c1::PREGNACY}} Can Cross placenta. bad for baby nose bones. 
Distinguishing Characteristics: {{c1::Slow}} onset 150  hours (2-7 days).
Highly plasma protein bound. Metabolized by CYP {{c1::P450 2C9}}
(Clotting inducers: Barbiturates, {{c1::carbamazepine}}, {{c1:phenytoin}})
(Bleeding Inhibitors: fluconazole, erythromycin, sulfamethoxazole).

Narrow therapeutic index so need to keep INR 2-3 (PT/normal PT =1)
Antidote {{c1::Vitamin K}} or rapid fresh or frozen {{c1::plasma}} in emergency.

Antihyperlipidemics
Atorvastatin
Treat:  {{c1::Hyperlipidemia}}
MOA: Reversibly and competitively inhibit {{c1::HMG-CoA reductase}}, which results in an increase in {{c1::LDL receptors}} to pull LDL out of blood.
ADR:  {{c1::Myopathy}}, {{c1::Rhabdomyolysis}}, Liver Damage
Distinguishing Characteristics: Decrease LDL by up to {{c1::55}}%. Some liver toxicity.

Antihyperlipidemics
Ezetimibe
Treat: 
MOA: Inhibits cholesterol absorption in intestinal jejunum ({{c1::NPC1L1}}, Niemann-Pick C1-like 1 cholesterol absorption receptor). causes upregulation of{{c1:: LDL receptor.}}
ADR: not absorbed, well tolerated.
Distinguishing Characteristics: Decrease LDL by up to {{c1::20}}%

Antihyperlipidemics
AliroCumab
Treat: {{c1::Heterozygous familial hypercholesterolemia}}
MOA: Block {{c1::PCSK9}} which binds to LDLRs on the surface of hepatocytes to promote LDLR degradation within the liver. Increases {{c1::LDL receptor}} number to clear LDL,
ADR: Injection side irritation, Anaphylaxis,
Distinguishing Characteristics: reduce LDL by 48-{{c1::71}}%
"Most famous boxing champion of the mabs. "

DNA synthesis inhibitors 
 
Anti-metabolite (S phase)
 
Methotrexate (MTX)
Treat: 
MOA: similar to folate, blocks {{c1::dihydrofolate}} reductase by blocking folate cofactor, cant make dTmp ({{c1::thymidine}}), purine ring, and the amino acids ser and met. so prevents DNA replication {{c1::S}} phase.
ADR:  Megaloblastic anemia, hair loss, Anemia, leukopenia, GI Upset, impared {{c1::sperm}} forming cells, impaired {{c1::healing}}, {{c1::teratogenesis}} (1st trimester)
ANTIDOTE: {{c1::Leucovorin}} (folinic acid)

DNA synthesis inhibitors 
 
Anti-metabolite (S phase)

5-Fluorouracil (5-FU)
Treat: 
MOA: 5-Fu goes to 5-{{c1::FdUMP}}, which competitively Inhibits {{c1::thymidylate synthesis}} of dTMP, block U in mRNA and T in DNA. Prevents DNA replication {{c1::S}} phase.
ADR: Nausea, mucositis, diarrhea; Hand and foot syndrome (red swollen hands/feet); Alopecia; BM depression
Distinguishing Characteristics: Commonly combined with {{c1::leucovorin}}, which increases efficacy of 5-FU

DNA synthesis inhibitors 
 
Anti-metabolite (S phase)

6-Mercaptopurine (6-MP)
Treat: 
MOA: 6-MP inhibits {{c1::purine}} synthases (A G) by blocking TIMP: {{c1::thio-inosine monophosphate}}.  Prevents DNA replication {{c1::S}} phase.
ADR: All common side effects like BM depression
Distinguishing Characteristics: allopurinol can help prevent excess uric acid (Tumor acid syndrome?) , but need to reduce 6-MP dose by 60% to prevent toxcisity
"6-MercaptoPURINE blocks PURINE synth"

Distinguishing Characteristics:
